This paper deals with text analytics and statistical topic modelling, which are commonly studied in the sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also focuses on analyzing Twitter data, which falls under the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper deals with large volumes of dynamic text, which can be analyzed using techniques from the sub-category of Software Engineering (cs.SE) and Systems and Control (cs.SY). The paper also uses evaluation measures such as Normalized Mutual Information (NMI) and topic coherence analysis, which are commonly used in the sub-categories of Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Cybersecurity (cs.CY). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories for this paper are cs.CL and cs.SI, followed by cs.SD, cs.IR, and cs.CY.
